column1: A wide area network ( WAN ) is a telecommunications network that extends over a large geographic area . WANs are commonly connected to the local area network (LANs) which are geographically smaller. The term WAN was first used to describe telecommunications network connections over long distance. Later
column2: the term was used to describe the connections used by computer systems over long distance telecommunication lines.|0

Emissions trading is a market-based approach to controlling pollution by providing economic incentives for reducing the emissions of pollutants. The concept is also known as cap and trade (CAT) or emissions trading scheme (ETS). Carbon emission trading for  and other greenhouse gases has been introduced in China, the European Union and other countries as a key tool for climate change mitigation. Other schemes include sulfur dioxide and other pollutants.In an emissions trading scheme, a central authority or governmental body allocates or sells a limited number (a "cap") of permits that allow a discharge of a specific quantity of a specific pollutant over a set time period.|1

Many factors are involved when determining whether a slope will fail and what type of landslides will be produced.|0

column1: The Magic Flute ( German : , ) , K. 620 , is an opera in two acts by Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart to a German-language libretto by Emanuel Schikaneder. Mozart had been commissioned to produce an opera for the carnival season, and began work almost immediately, finishing the music in just over two weeks. The libretto, which Mozart described as "ridiculous nonsense", was an adaption of a fairy tale by the German author Johann Hoffmann von Krasnik, with a few incidents from other sources added.|0

column1: An inverse multiplexer ( often abbreviated to inverse MUX or IMUX ) allows a data stream to be broken into multiple data streams, and recombined later into one. In other words, the data stream is "divided and conquered". This makes it a useful component in the design of high-bandwidth communication systems which can transmit information across multiple channels, which can all be modulated in the same way. In telephony , an IMUX is used to convert 30 channels into 1 channel. The multiplexed channels can be either T1 (24 voice channels) or E1 (30 voice channels.)|0

column1: Thrust is a reaction force described quantitatively by Newton 's third law . When a system expels or accelerates mass in one direction, an equal but opposite force acts in the direction opposite of motion. The magnitude of the force, F, acting on a body of mass m is given by: F = m.a, where: a = acceleration of body m = mass (kg) F = force acting on the body, m x a = 1/2.m.a2 = constant of proportionality. This quantity is often taken as the definition of the "moment" of a force about a point.|0

The Soma cube is a solid dissection puzzle invented by Danish polymath Piet Hein in 1933 during a lecture on the nature of infinity. It can be considered the first commercially produced "modern" polyhedral puzzle (i.e. a puzzle invented after the 1920s). Although it was originally designed in 1934, the first commercial production occurred in 1936. The Soma Cube is a 4x4x4 puzzle, with each side having a number of triangles. In total, there are 480 pieces, and the objective is to put them all together to form the solid object.|0

column1: The oxidation state, or oxidation number, is the hypothetical charge of an atom if all of its bonds to different atoms were fully ionic. It describes the degree of oxidation (loss of electrons) of an atom in a chemical compound. Conceptually, the oxidation state may be positive, negative or zero. While fully ionic bonds are not found in nature, many bonds exhibit strong ionicity, making oxidation state a useful predictor of charge.The oxidation state of an atom does not represent the "real" formal charge on that atom, or any other actual atomic property.|1

column1: In mathematics , the Dirac delta distribution ( distribution ) , also known as the unit impulse symbol , is a generalized function that has the value at every point in a space, and has a continuous derivative of value zero. The name "delta function" has been used for a number of distributions, this one is also known as the Kronecker delta function. It is named after the physicist P A M Dirac , and denoted by the upper Greek letter. This article explains the basic properties of the Dirac delta function and gives a formula for the delta distribution to get a point.|0

column1: The Novikov self-consistency principle, also known as the Novikov self-consistency conjecture and Larry Niven's law of conservation of history, is a principle developed by Russian physicist Igor Dmitriyevich Novikov in the mid-1980s. It was first introduced to the public in Martin Gardner's March 1963 Mathematical Games column in Scientific American magazine.There is no consensus on its precise nature and consequently a canonical resolution has not been agreed on. Logical analyses focus on "truth values", for example by identifying it as paradox of self-reference.|1

column1: Shakespearean tragedy is the designation given to most tragedies written by playwright William Shakespeare . However, Shakespeare's most famous and influential tragedies include Romeo and Juliet , Othello , King Lear , Macbeth , and Antony and Cleopatra . column1: A frog is any member of a diverse and largely carnivorous group of short-bodied, tailless amphibians composing the order Anura (literally without tail in Ancient Greek). column7: which are much less efficient. Monopropellants also have the advantage of being stored at atmospheric pressure

Fermat's principle, also known as the principle of least time, is the link between ray optics and wave optics. In order to be true in all cases, this statement must be weakened by replacing the "least" time with a time that is "stationary" with respect to variations of the path — so that a deviation in the path causes, at most, a second-order change in the traversal time.|1

The idea was introduced by David Hilbert in a 1924 lecture "Über das Unendliche", reprinted in , and was popularized through George Gamow's 1947 book One Two Three... The Burrows–Wheeler transform (BWT, also called block-sorting compression) rearranges a character string into runs of similar characters. This is useful for compression, since it tends to be easy to compress a string that has runs of repeated characters by techniques such as move-to-front transform and run-length encoding. More importantly, the transformation is reversible, without needing to store any additional data except the position of the first original character. The BWT is thus a "free" method of improving the efficiency of text compression algorithms, costing only some extra computation.|1

The covalent radius , rcov , is a measure of the size of an atom that forms part of one of the following types of bonds:
double bond (C≡C, C≡N, S≡S)
triple bond (O≡O, O≡N)
The bond distance of a double bond in which the two atoms share two electrons, such as the carbon double bond in ethene, is 1.540 Å. The bond distance of a triple bond in which the atoms share three electrons, such as in ethynyl anion, is 1.61 Å. The covalent radius can be determined by either the electronegativity difference or the electron affinity difference.|0

The Alcubierre drive , Alcubierre warp drive , or Alcubierre metric ( referring to metric tensor ) , is a speculative idea for faster-than-light or warp drive propulsion system for spacecraft in which a spacetime distortion is created, using a kind of exotic matter , which would bend spacetime, much the same as in a wormhole. However, rather than relying on matter to connect separate regions of spacetime, Alcubierre proposed the distortion could be achieved by applying a "negative energy density" to the spacecraft itself, which creates a "pseudotime" surface inside the bubble, moving the ship from one point to another in the space-time surrounding it.|0
